import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

sns.set_style("whitegrid")
sns.set_context("notebook", font_scale=1.2)

# Create a joint plot
sns.jointplot(x='danceability', y='popularity', data=df, kind='scatter', color='#1db954')

# Set labels and title
plt.xlabel('Danceability')
plt.ylabel('Popularity')
plt.suptitle('Distribution and Relationship: Danceability vs. Popularity', y=1.02)

# Show the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

By looking at the jointplot we can see that there is positive correlation between popularity and dancebility. We can also see the distribution of variables, on the top we see dancebility which slightly skewed towards left while popularity is slightly skewed towrds right.

Exploring the Spread of Spotify Audio Features¶

In [ ]:
# Select the relevant columns from the df dataframe
hist_spotify = df[['duration_ms', 'popularity', 'danceability', 'energy', 'loudness', 'speechiness', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness', 'liveness', 'valence', 'tempo']]

# Set the figure size and layout
fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=5, ncols=2, figsize=(15, 20))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.5)

# Plot histograms for each variable in the dataframe
for ax, col in zip(axes.flatten(), hist_spotify.columns):
    ax.hist(hist_spotify[col], bins=30, color='#1db954', edgecolor='black', alpha=0.7, histtype='bar')
    ax.set_title(col, fontsize=14)
    ax.set_xlabel(col, fontsize=12)
    ax.set_ylabel('Frequency', fontsize=12)

# Display the plot
plt.suptitle('Spotify Audio Features', fontsize=20)
plt.show()

This generated set of histograms help us visualize the distribution of different audio features in the Spotify dataset.

  • duration_ms - The distribution of track duration in milliseconds. Shows the number of songs across different duration ranges.

  • popularity - The distribution of popularity scores for tracks. Indicates how many songs have low, medium or high popularity.

  • danceability - Distribution of danceability scores from 0 to 1. Higher values indicate more suitable for dancing.

  • energy - Distribution of energy scores from 0 to 1. Higher values are more energetic/intense songs.

  • loudness - Distribution of loudness in decibels (dB). Shows variation in loudness across tracks.

  • speechiness - Distribution of speechiness scores from 0 to 1. Higher values have more spoken words.

  • acousticness - Distribution of acousticness scores from 0 to 1. Higher means more acoustic.

  • instrumentalness - Distribution of instrumentalness scores from 0 to 1. Higher indicates more instrumental content.

  • liveness - Distribution of liveness scores from 0 to 1. Higher is more likely a live recording.

  • valence - Distribution of valence scores from 0 to 1. Higher indicates more positive mood.

  • tempo - Distribution of tempo in beats per minute (BPM). Visualizes tempo variation.

Overall, these histograms allow us to visualize the spread and shape of each audio feature's distribution across the full set of tracks. We can see centers, variation, outliers etc. This supports understanding the musical qualities and diversity.

This is a correlation matrix showing the Pearson correlation coefficients between each pair of variables in the dataset. Let's go through some key observations:

  • Popularity is positively correlated with danceability, energy, and loudness. So more popular songs tend to be more danceable, energetic, and loud.

  • Popularity is negatively correlated with acousticness and instrumentalness. So more popular songs tend to be less acoustic and instrumental.

  • Danceability is positively correlated with energy and valence. More danceable songs tend to be more energetic and have higher valence (positivity).

  • Energy is strongly positively correlated with loudness. More energetic songs also tend to be louder.

  • Speechiness is positively correlated with liveness. More speechy tracks also tend to have higher liveness.

  • Loudness is negatively correlated with acousticness. Louder songs tend to be less acoustic.

  • Most correlations are weak to moderate. The strongest correlations are energy with loudness (0.82) and acousticness with energy (-0.73).

This gives a sense of which audio features are interrelated and how they relate to popularity. These correlations can help guide modeling choices and interpretation.

Let's go through the key parts of the output from an Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) linear regression model:

R-squared: 0.220

  • The R-squared shows how much variance in the dependent variable (popularity) is explained by the independent variables in the model. A value of 0.220 indicates that 22% of the variability in popularity is explained by this model.

F-statistic: 8224

  • The F-test assesses if the independent variables are jointly significant. The large F-value and p-value of 0 indicates there is a relationship between the independent variables and the dependent variable.

Coefficients - These show the estimated effect of each independent variable on popularity:

  • danceability: Positive coefficient of 21.7 - a higher danceability score is associated with higher popularity. Statistically significant relationship.

  • energy: Positive coefficient of 5.8 - more energetic songs tend to have higher popularity. Significant.

  • acousticness: Negative coefficient of -6.3 - more acoustic tracks have lower popularity. Significant.

  • instrumentalness: Negative coefficient of -7.3 - more instrumental tracks have lower popularity. Significant.

  • liveness: Negative coefficient of -10.4 - tracks with more liveness have lower popularity. Significant.

  • speechiness: Negative coefficient of -11.3 - more speechy tracks have lower popularity. Significant.

  • tempo and valence are not statistically significant in the model.

In summary, the OLS regression shows acoustic features like danceability, energy, acousticness, etc. have significant linear relationships with popularity, although the model only explains 22% of variance.

Anova¶

In [4]:
from scipy import stats

# Create popularity groups
df['popularity_group'] = pd.cut(df['popularity'],
                           bins=[0, 33, 66, 100],
                           labels=['low', 'medium', 'high'])

# Define factor for ANOVA
factor = df['popularity_group']

# Perform ANOVA for each feature
features = ['danceability', 'energy', 'acousticness', 'instrumentalness',
            'liveness', 'speechiness', 'tempo', 'valence']

for feature in features:

    data = df[feature]
    f_val, p_val = stats.f_oneway(data[factor=='low'],
                                  data[factor=='medium'],
                                  data[factor=='high'])

    print(feature)
    print('F value: ', f_val)
    print('P value: ', p_val)
    print()

Based on the ANOVA results, we can make the following interpretations:

  • The F-values for all the features are quite large, indicating there are significant differences in the means of the low, medium and high popularity groups for each of the audio features.

  • The p-values for all features except tempo are 0.0. This means there is extremely strong evidence (p<0.001) to reject the null hypothesis that the population means of the 3 groups are equal.

  • For tempo, the p-value is very small but not 0. There is still extremely strong evidence (p<0.001) to reject the null and conclude the tempo means differ between popularity groups.

In simple terms:

  • The songs in the low, medium and high popularity groups tend to significantly differ in terms of danceability, energy, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, speechiness, tempo and valence.

  • The differences in means of these audio features between the 3 groups are much larger than we would expect by chance.

  • So the popularity level of a song is associated with its audio features like danceability, energy etc. Songs with different popularity have detectable differences in their musical characteristics.

In [5]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Create cross-tabulation
contigency = pd.crosstab(df['genre'], df['popularity_group'])

# Perform chi-square test
chi2, p_val, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contigency)

# Print results
print("Chi-Square test results:")
print("Chi-Square value:", chi2)
print("P-value:", p_val)
print("Degrees of freedom:", dof)

# Interpret
if p_val < 0.05:
  print("Reject null hypothesis - there is a relationship between genre and popularity group")
else:
  print("Fail to reject null hypothesis - the variables are independent")

Chi-Square test results:
Chi-Square value: 154303.15328424354
P-value: 0.0
Degrees of freedom: 52
Reject null hypothesis - there is a relationship between genre and popularity group

Based on the chi-square test results, we can make the following interpretations:

  • The chi-square value of 154,303 is quite large. This suggests there is a significant relationship between the variables.

  • The p-value is 0.0, which is extremely statistically significant.

  • There are 52 degrees of freedom, which corresponds to the (number of rows - 1) x (number of columns - 1) for the contigency table.

  • Since the p-value is < 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis.

In simple terms:

  • There is a significant association between music genre and popularity group (low, medium, high).

  • The genre of a song is related to whether its popularity level is low, medium or high.

  • The distribution of music genres is different across low, medium and high popularity groups.

  • So we can conclude that music genre and song popularity are not independent - knowing a song's genre gives some information about whether it's likely to have low, medium or high popularity.

Overall, the chi-square test confirms that genre and popularity group are related variables in this dataset. The association is highly statistically significant.

Conclusion¶

In summary, this paper conducted a thorough analysis of Spotify's extensive dataset to uncover the complex connections among song audio features, lyrical sentiment, and track popularity. Through Python libraries and data visualization, valuable insights emerged, shedding light on the determinants of music track appeal on Spotify.

Initial data exploration revealed key aspects of the dataset, offering insights into audio feature distributions. Correlation analysis highlighted the impact of attributes like danceability, energy, acousticness, instrumentalness, liveness, and speechiness on track popularity, explaining 22% of the variance. This indicated the significance of certain acoustic traits in shaping perceived popularity.

ANOVA and chi-square tests confirmed that both audio features and genre play vital roles in defining track popularity. Different popularity levels exhibited distinct musical characteristics, with genres influencing a song's potential for low, medium, or high popularity.

In essence, this study underscores the interplay of audio features, lyrical sentiment, and genre in determining music track popularity on Spotify. While the analysis offers valuable insights, it's crucial to acknowledge that music appreciation remains subjective and multifaceted. As the digital music landscape evolves, this study provides foundational insights for musicians, enthusiasts, and industry stakeholders into the intricate dynamics that contribute to a song's appeal.
